				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$B_r^0(\theta, \phi) = \sum\limits_{l = 1}^\infty {} \sum\limits_{m = - l}^{ + l} {{b_{lm}}} {y_{lm}}(\theta, \phi).$$\end{document} Now at high Rm, under the joint action of differential rotation and magnetic dissipation, all non-axisymmetric (i.e., m ≠ 0) terms will be destroyed on a timescale much faster than diffusive, a process known as axisymmetrization that is the spherical equivalent of the well-known process of magnetic flux expulsion by closed circulatory flows. Therefore, after some time the surface radial field will assume the form 16\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
